ce:section.ce:para:
To explore the binding mode of these probes toward Fe3+, Job's plot analysis was carried out with the total concentration of the representative probe and Fe3+ solutions being constant, and the [MP-Gal-1]/[MP-Gal-1 + Fe

                           3+
                        ] value varying from 0.1 to 0.9 (Fig. 4
                        ). When the [MP-Gal-1]/[MP-Gal-1 + Fe

                           3+
                        ] value was about 1/3, the solution emitted the strongest fluorescence, indicating that 1 equiv. MP-Gal-1 was most likely to bind 2 equiv. Fe3+ ion. Therefore, 1: 2 stoichiometry was deemed as the most recognition mode of the probe toward Fe3+. In view of the fact that it is difficult for the probes containing sugar structure to form crystals with Fe3+ ions, we cannot obtain the crystal structure of the iron(III)-MP-Gal-1 complex, although many efforts have been made. However, to further confirm the 1:2 recognition pattern of the aimed probes toward Fe3+, we performed a mass spectrometry study on the iron(III)-MP-Gal-1 complex. As shown in Fig. S2, ESI-MS spectrum data of the iron(III)-MP-Gal-1 complex support the binding mode of the aimed probes toward Fe3+. Among these two equiv. Fe3+ ions, one equiv. Fe3+ might bind to the piperazine nitrogen of MP-Gal-1, inhibiting the PET effect from electrondonator piperazine to electron-receptor 1,8-naphthalimide moiety and recovering the strong fluorescence of 1,8-naphthalimide.
